# XtendR_Csharp, Version 0
# by John L. Darcy
# This program takes contigs from a genome assembly and extends them. 
# This process can join multiple contigs together using raw reads. 

# To run this program on linux (no idea how to do it on other OSs...):
# 1. Install mono
# 2. Download or clone this repository
# 3. In a terminal, run:
      mono path_to_downloaded_folder/Xtendr_Csharp/bin/Debug/XtendR_Csharp.exe -h
#     That should show the help documentation, which I'll paste below.
# 4. Read the help, figure out your inputs, and run! Note that your raw reads
      need to be in fasta format, not fastq. 
 
# Arguments: 
# 
#  -f, --fasta                 Required. Raw sequences filepath; fasta format; 
#                              REQUIRED
#
#  -s, --startContig           Required. Starting contig filepath; fasta format;
#                              REQUIRED
#
#  -k, --kmerLength            Required. kmer length; integer; REQUIRED; suggest
#                              20% of raw sequence length.
#
#  -l, --lengthTarget          Required. Target addition length; integer; 
#                              REQUIRED.
#
#  -o, --output                Required. Output filepath; fasta format; REQUIRED
#
#  -c, --contigs               (Default: not used) Assembled contigs filepath; 
#                              fasta format; optional.
#
#  -p, --contigOverlap         (Default: 300) Number of NTs that must match 
#                              between a contig and the current assembled 
#                              sequence for the contig to be added; integer; 
#                              default=300
#
#  -y, --consensusThreshold    (Default: 3) number of agreeing NTs required in 
#                              an alignment column for consensus; integer; 
#                              default=2.
#
#  -m, --minKmerHits           (Default: 8) Minimum number of kmer hits required
#                              for each iteration; integer; default=8
#
#  -r, --recoveryTrim          (Default: 45) Number of NTs to trim if enough 
#                              kmers can't be found; integer; default=45; 
#                              suggest a bit more than kmer length.
#
#  -t, --threadsMax            (Default: 12) Maximum number of CPU threads to be
#                              used for parallel kmer searches; integer; 
#                              default=12
#
#  -q, --quiet                 Silences helpful messages generated by this 
#                              program. Remember, the default verbose output IS 
#                              your log (i.e. it's up to you to use >log.txt).
#
#  -x, --citation              Displays citation information for this program.
#
#  -j, --joke                  Tells you a funny joke before running the 
#                              assembly.
#
#  -h, --help                  Displays this friendly help dialog. Email me if 
#                              you're having REAL trouble.
